Without any improvements to the code beyond what is necessary, you should utilize the type provided by your `Class` parameter:

    public &lt;T&gt; ArrayList&lt;T&gt; getListObject(String key, Class&lt;T&gt; mClass){ //change 1
        Gson gson = new Gson();
    
        ArrayList&lt;String&gt; objStrings = getListString(key);
        ArrayList&lt;T&gt; objects =  new ArrayList&lt;&gt;(); //change 2
    
        for(String jObjString : objStrings){
            T value  = gson.fromJson(jObjString,  mClass); //change 3
            objects.add(value);
        }
        return objects;
    }

Regarding the changes above:

 

 1. Introducing `&lt;T&gt;` is declaring a generic type parameter _on the method_. When we then declare `mClass` as a `Class&lt;T&gt;`, we say that `T` is an instance of the class type you passed. By returning `ArrayList&lt;T&gt;`, we&#39;re returning a list of objects that have the type you provided.
 2. Our returned value is changed accordingly, so that we truly return a `List&lt;T&gt;`. The second `Object` is dropped in favor of the diamond operator `new ArrayList&lt;&gt;()`, as re-declaring the type is not necessary in Java 7+
 3. We utilize the generic return value from `Gson#fromJson` which does a similar approach to what we&#39;ve done above. This allows us to get a `T` value instead of just an `Object`, which we add to our result list.

As noted in the comments, there are means of retrieving list values from gson (e.g. a `TypeAdapter` or even type tokens), but the solution above is to demonstrate fixing the problem with raw types and invariant types for generics (`List&lt;String&gt; != List&lt;Number&gt;` for most contexts).

