## Reading the JSON documents as `Map`s and comparing them

You could read both JSON documents as [`Map&lt;K, V&gt;`][1]. See the below examples for Jackson and Gson:
    
&lt;!-- language: lang-java --&gt;
    
    ObjectMapper mapper = new ObjectMapper();
    TypeReference&lt;HashMap&lt;String, Object&gt;&gt; type = 
        new TypeReference&lt;HashMap&lt;String, Object&gt;&gt;() {};
    
    Map&lt;String, Object&gt; leftMap = mapper.readValue(leftJson, type);
    Map&lt;String, Object&gt; rightMap = mapper.readValue(rightJson, type);

&lt;!-- language: lang-java --&gt;

    Gson gson = new Gson();
    Type type = new TypeToken&lt;Map&lt;String, Object&gt;&gt;(){}.getType();
    
    Map&lt;String, Object&gt; leftMap = gson.fromJson(leftJson, type);
    Map&lt;String, Object&gt; rightMap = gson.fromJson(rightJson, type);
    
Then use Guava&#39;s [`Maps.difference(Map&lt;K, V&gt;, Map&lt;K, V&gt;)`][2] to compare them. It returns a [`MapDifference&lt;K, V&gt;`][3] instance:

&lt;!-- language: lang-java --&gt;
    
    MapDifference&lt;String, Object&gt; difference = Maps.difference(leftMap, rightMap);
    
If you are not happy with the result, you can consider **flattening** the maps and then compare them. It will provide better comparison results especially for nested objects and arrays.
    
## Creating flat `Map`s for the comparison

To flat the map, you can use:

&lt;!-- language: lang-java --&gt;

    public final class FlatMapUtil {

        private FlatMapUtil() {
            throw new AssertionError(&quot;No instances for you!&quot;);
        }

        public static Map&lt;String, Object&gt; flatten(Map&lt;String, Object&gt; map) {
            return map.entrySet().stream()
                    .flatMap(FlatMapUtil::flatten)
                    .collect(LinkedHashMap::new, (m, e) -&gt; m.put(&quot;/&quot; + e.getKey(), e.getValue()), LinkedHashMap::putAll);
        }

        private static Stream&lt;Map.Entry&lt;String, Object&gt;&gt; flatten(Map.Entry&lt;String, Object&gt; entry) {

            if (entry == null) {
                return Stream.empty();
            }

            if (entry.getValue() instanceof Map&lt;?, ?&gt;) {
                return ((Map&lt;?, ?&gt;) entry.getValue()).entrySet().stream()
                        .flatMap(e -&gt; flatten(new AbstractMap.SimpleEntry&lt;&gt;(entry.getKey() + &quot;/&quot; + e.getKey(), e.getValue())));
            }

            if (entry.getValue() instanceof List&lt;?&gt;) {
                List&lt;?&gt; list = (List&lt;?&gt;) entry.getValue();
                return IntStream.range(0, list.size())
                        .mapToObj(i -&gt; new AbstractMap.SimpleEntry&lt;String, Object&gt;(entry.getKey() + &quot;/&quot; + i, list.get(i)))
                        .flatMap(FlatMapUtil::flatten);
            }

            return Stream.of(entry);
        }
    }

It uses the _JSON Pointer notation_ defined in the [RFC 6901][4] for the keys, so you can easily locate the values.
    
## Example

Consider the following JSON documents:

&lt;!-- language: lang-json --&gt;

    {
      &quot;name&quot;: {
        &quot;first&quot;: &quot;John&quot;,
        &quot;last&quot;: &quot;Doe&quot;
      },
      &quot;address&quot;: null,
      &quot;birthday&quot;: &quot;1980-01-01&quot;,
      &quot;company&quot;: &quot;Acme&quot;,
      &quot;occupation&quot;: &quot;Software engineer&quot;,
      &quot;phones&quot;: [
        {
          &quot;number&quot;: &quot;000000000&quot;,
          &quot;type&quot;: &quot;home&quot;
        },
        {
          &quot;number&quot;: &quot;999999999&quot;,
          &quot;type&quot;: &quot;mobile&quot;
        }
      ]
    }
    
&lt;!-- language: lang-json --&gt;
    
    {
      &quot;name&quot;: {
        &quot;first&quot;: &quot;Jane&quot;,
        &quot;last&quot;: &quot;Doe&quot;,
        &quot;nickname&quot;: &quot;Jenny&quot;
      },
      &quot;birthday&quot;: &quot;1990-01-01&quot;,
      &quot;occupation&quot;: null,
      &quot;phones&quot;: [
        {
          &quot;number&quot;: &quot;111111111&quot;,
          &quot;type&quot;: &quot;mobile&quot;
        }
      ],
      &quot;favorite&quot;: true,
      &quot;groups&quot;: [
        &quot;close-friends&quot;,
        &quot;gym&quot;
      ]
    }

And the following code to compare them and show the differences:

&lt;!-- language: lang-java --&gt;
    
    Map&lt;String, Object&gt; leftFlatMap = FlatMapUtil.flatten(leftMap);
    Map&lt;String, Object&gt; rightFlatMap = FlatMapUtil.flatten(rightMap);

    MapDifference&lt;String, Object&gt; difference = Maps.difference(leftFlatMap, rightFlatMap);

    System.out.println(&quot;Entries only on the left\n--------------------------&quot;);
    difference.entriesOnlyOnLeft()
              .forEach((key, value) -&gt; System.out.println(key + &quot;: &quot; + value));

    System.out.println(&quot;\n\nEntries only on the right\n--------------------------&quot;);
    difference.entriesOnlyOnRight()
              .forEach((key, value) -&gt; System.out.println(key + &quot;: &quot; + value));

    System.out.println(&quot;\n\nEntries differing\n--------------------------&quot;);
    difference.entriesDiffering()
              .forEach((key, value) -&gt; System.out.println(key + &quot;: &quot; + value));
    
It will produce the following output:

&lt;!-- language: lang-none --&gt;

    Entries only on the left
    --------------------------
    /address: null
    /phones/1/number: 999999999
    /phones/1/type: mobile
    /company: Acme


    Entries only on the right
    --------------------------
    /name/nickname: Jenny
    /groups/0: close-friends
    /groups/1: gym
    /favorite: true


    Entries differing
    --------------------------
    /birthday: (1980-01-01, 1990-01-01)
    /occupation: (Software engineer, null)
    /name/first: (John, Jane)
    /phones/0/number: (000000000, 111111111)
    /phones/0/type: (home, mobile)

    
  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/10/docs/api/java/util/Map.html
  [2]: https://google.github.io/guava/releases/snapshot/api/docs/com/google/common/collect/Maps.html#difference-java.util.Map-java.util.Map-
  [3]: https://google.github.io/guava/releases/snapshot/api/docs/com/google/common/collect/MapDifference.html
  [4]: https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc6901

## Creating a JSON Patch document

Alternatively to the approach described in the [other answer][1], you could use the [Java API for JSON Processing][2] defined in the [JSR 374][3] (it doesn&#39;t use on Gson or Jackson). The following dependencies are required:

&lt;!-- language: lang-xml --&gt;
	
	&lt;!-- Java API for JSON Processing (API) --&gt;
	&lt;dependency&gt;
		&lt;groupId&gt;javax.json&lt;/groupId&gt;
		&lt;artifactId&gt;javax.json-api&lt;/artifactId&gt;
		&lt;version&gt;1.1.2&lt;/version&gt;
	&lt;/dependency&gt;

	&lt;!-- Java API for JSON Processing (implementation) --&gt;
	&lt;dependency&gt;
		&lt;groupId&gt;org.glassfish&lt;/groupId&gt;
		&lt;artifactId&gt;javax.json&lt;/artifactId&gt;
		&lt;version&gt;1.1.2&lt;/version&gt;
	&lt;/dependency&gt;

Then you can create a JSON diff from the JSON documents. It will produce a JSON Patch document as defined in the [RFC 6902][4]:

&lt;!-- language: lang-java --&gt;

    JsonPatch diff = Json.createDiff(source, target);

When applied to the source document, the JSON Patch yields the target document. The JSON Patch can be applied to the source document using:

&lt;!-- language: lang-java --&gt;	

    JsonObject patched = diff.apply(source);
	
## Creating a JSON Merge Patch document

Depending on your needs, you could create a JSON Merge Patch document as defined in the [RFC 7396][5]:

&lt;!-- language: lang-java --&gt;

    JsonMergePatch mergeDiff = Json.createMergeDiff(source, target);

When applied to the source document, the JSON Merge Patch yields the target document. To patch the source, use:

&lt;!-- language: lang-java --&gt;

    JsonValue patched = mergeDiff.apply(source);

## Pretty printing JSON documents
	
To pretty print the JSON documents, you can use:

&lt;!-- language: lang-java --&gt;

    System.out.println(format(diff.toJsonArray()));
	System.out.println(format(mergeDiff.toJsonValue()));
	
&lt;!-- language: lang-java --&gt;

    public static String format(JsonValue json) {
        StringWriter stringWriter = new StringWriter();
        prettyPrint(json, stringWriter);
        return stringWriter.toString();
    }

    public static void prettyPrint(JsonValue json, Writer writer) {
        Map&lt;String, Object&gt; config =
                Collections.singletonMap(JsonGenerator.PRETTY_PRINTING, true);
        JsonWriterFactory writerFactory = Json.createWriterFactory(config);
        try (JsonWriter jsonWriter = writerFactory.createWriter(writer)) {
            jsonWriter.write(json);
        }
    }
	
## Example

Consider the following JSON documents:

&lt;!-- language: lang-json --&gt;

	{
	  &quot;name&quot;: {
		&quot;first&quot;: &quot;John&quot;,
		&quot;last&quot;: &quot;Doe&quot;
	  },
	  &quot;address&quot;: null,
	  &quot;birthday&quot;: &quot;1980-01-01&quot;,
